## Container Complexity — What You're Managing

### Lifecycle Management
- Registry of which sandboxes are alive, which tenant they belong to, current state
- Cold start latency: Vercel Sandbox boots in sub-seconds (Firecracker), but first-time setup (npm install, file loading) takes longer
- Strategy: pre-seed common dependencies via snapshots, then clone per tenant

### State Hydration & Teardown
- Each sandbox boots empty on first creation. Load: system prompt, skill files, uploaded documents, conversation history from Supabase
- On teardown: extract results, persist back to Supabase before sandbox sleeps
- With Vercel persistent sandboxes, filesystem survives — so you only hydrate once per tenant

### Idle Timeout Tuning
- WhatsApp conversations are bursty (3 messages/minute then silence for hours)
- Keep alive = $0.128/hr per sandbox. Kill + cold start = latency penalty
- Vercel's persistent sandboxes solve this: filesystem saved for free when idle, compute cost only when active

### Resource Contention
- Each sandbox: ~1 GiB RAM minimum
- 100 concurrent users = 100 GiB RAM at peak
- OOM risk: the SDK can OOM if agents use multiple subagents without resource management
- Set `maxTurns` to cap runaway loops

### Networking & Credential Injection
- Each sandbox needs outbound HTTPS to api.anthropic.com + your Supabase endpoint
- Vercel Sandbox supports credentials brokering — injects secrets on egress, never enters sandbox scope
- Prevents tenant data cross-contamination

### Observability
- Standard logging/monitoring (Datadog, Grafana) works since containers are just servers
- Vercel provides Observability → Sandboxes view with real-time log streaming
- Agent sessions don't timeout, but set `maxTurns` to prevent infinite loops

